d and the life stories of two kinds of funeral workers: state workers who are quasi-government officials and semi-legal private funeral brokers. She shows that end-of-life commemoration in urban China today is characterized by the resilience of social conventions and not a shift toward market economy individualization. Rather than seeing a rise of individualism and the decline of a socialist self, Liu sees the durability of socialist, religious, communal, and relational ideas of self, woven together through creative ritual framings in spite of their contradictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aDeath care industryxGovernment ownershipzChina. 0aDeath care industryxGovernment policyzChina. 0aFuneral rites and ceremoniesxGovernment policyzChina. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonieszChinazShanghai. 4aANTHROPOLOGY. 4aAsian Studies. 4aSOCIOLOGY & SOCIAL SCIENCE. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  afuneral parlors in china, funeral governance in china, shanghai funeral industry, chinese death rituals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176723440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767234/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK